g developments: Japanese economic penetration of Asian supplier networks through a system of production alliances, and the emergence of a pan-Pacific trading region that includes both Asia and North America. The contributors emphasize factors that are creating an Asia marked by multiple centers of influence, including China and the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 4aAsian Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History.1 aKatzenstein, Peter J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aShiraishi, Takashi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Packagez978311064968008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173145740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501731457423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501731457/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  a978-3-11-064968-0  Asian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Packageb2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles